Here's a Next.js code snippet for a sticky header using CSS:

```tsx
// components/StickyHeader.tsx
import Link from 'next/link';

export default function StickyHeader() {
  return (
    <header 
      style={{ 
        position: 'sticky',
        top: 0,
        backgroundColor: '#fff',
        zIndex: 10
      }}
      className="p-4 border-b"
    >
      <div className="container mx-auto flex justify-between items-center">
        <h1 className="text-xl font-bold">MySite</h1>
        <nav>
          <Link href="/">Home</Link>
          <Link href="/about">About</Link>
        </nav>
      </div>
    </header>
  );
}
```

```tsx
// pages/index.tsx
import StickyHeader from '../components/StickyHeader';

export default function Home() {
  return (
    <>
      <StickyHeader />
      <main className="p-4">
        <h2>Welcome to MySite!</h2>
        <p>Scroll down to see the sticky header in action.</p>
        <div style={{ height: '2000px' }}></div>
      </main>
    </>
  );
}
```

This implementation:
1. Uses `position: sticky` with `top: 0` to make the header stick to the top
2. Includes a simple navigation with Next.js links
3. Demonstrates how the header remains visible when scrolling
4. Adds a tall content area to showcase the sticky behavior

